{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617005"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:09:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:09:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16448"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16448","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16448"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9139"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75949"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9139"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16448"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61450"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1153"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"5932"},{"type":"tags","id":"7547"},{"type":"tags","id":"11205"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21706"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21708"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75949","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75949"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn patient presents complaining of double vision. You take a history and perform an examination. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the correct sequence for the (Parks-Bielschowsky) three-step test?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Determine head tilt effect, then gaze direction effect, then hypertropic eye","Determine gaze direction effect, then head tilt effect, then hypertropic eye","Determine hypertropic eye, then gaze direction effect, then head tilt effect","Determine hypertropic eye, then head tilt effect, then gaze direction effect","Determine gaze direction effect, then hypertropic eye, then head tilt effect"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Parks-Bielschowsky three-step test is a systematic approach to identifying which extraocular muscle is paretic in a patient presenting with \u003Cem\u003Evertical\u003C/em\u003E \u003Cem\u003Ediplopia\u003C/em\u003E. The test must be performed in the correct sequence to accurately isolate the affected muscle.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetermine hypertropic eye, then gaze direction effect, then head tilt effect\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct sequence. Step 1 identifies which eye is higher in primary position. Step 2 determines whether the vertical deviation increases in right or left gaze. Step 3 determines whether the deviation increases with head tilt to the right or left.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are thus incorrect. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy following the correct sequence, the clinician can systematically narrow down which of the four vertical rectus muscles or two oblique muscles is paretic. This information is crucial for both diagnosis and management planning.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The three-step test or Parks-Bielschowsky test is used to identify which extraocular muscle is paretic in vertical diplopia.","In the three step test, the examination must be performed in the correct sequence to accurately identify the paretic extraocular muscle.","A paretic extra ocular muscle, as identified by the three step test, can be a cause of vertical diplopia."],"references":["Manchandia AM, Demer JL. Sensitivity of the three-step test in diagnosis of superior oblique palsy. J AAPOS. 2014 Dec;18(6):567-71. doi: 10.1016/j.jaapos.2014.08.007. Epub 2014 Nov 12. PMID: 25459202; PMCID: PMC4268244.","Kumar A. Parks 3-step test. Indian J Ophthalmol. 2022 Aug;70(8):3167. doi: 10.4103/ijo.IJO_714_22. PMID: 35919015; PMCID: PMC9672736.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61450"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16448"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61450"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T14:59:20+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T14:59:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9139"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75949"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"